summary.value:
Previous research has found that Black/White and Asian/White multiracial individuals are racially categorized according to hypodescent (Ho, Sidanius, Levin, & Banaji, 2011), or that Multiracial individuals will be categorized as part of their lower status racial group (Banks & Eberhardt, 1998). In the current study, which is primarily exploratory, we test if other, previously unstudied, multiracial combinations Latino/White, Black/Asian, Black/Latino, and Latino/Asian are also categorized according to hypodescent, or as Latino, Black, Black, and Latino, respectively. If Black/White and Asian/White multiracial individuals are categorized according to hypodescent then other multiracial combinations should theoretically also be categorized according to hypodescent. Additionally, we were interested if hypodescent categorizations influence perceptions of how representative these Multiracial combinations are of the overall Multiracial group. 

Please see attached pdf file for the complete pre-registration for this study.

attributes.title: The Curse of Knowledge: How Second-best Solutions Affects Organizational Search

data.value: No, no data have been collected for this study yet.

name.value: The Curse of Knowledge: How Second-best Solutions Affect Organizational Search—Study 3

other.value:
As a secondary analysis, we will examine search distance, i.e., the extent to which participants deviate from their initial combination.

We will also conduct manipulation checks before participants initiate the experimental task. In particular, we will ask participants in the Control condition what profit they can expect to make if they try different combinations over 100 periods of running the lemonade stand. Participants in the Treatment condition will not only be asked this question, but they will also be asked what profit they can expect to make if they try the combination that they were informed of.

In line with the protocol followed by Ederer and Manso (2013), we will also collect data on our participants' risk and ambiguity aversion. For the former, we will ask our participants to make ten choices between lotteries of different expected values, as in Holt and Laury (2002). For the latter, we will ask our participants to make seven choices between two urns with different containing blue and red balls, each color paying a different amount of money, as in Ederer and Manso (2013).

We will also ask our participants 1) why they chose to participate in our study, 2) how old they are, 3) what their gender is, 4) what is the highest level of education that they completed, and 5) on what topic, or discipline, they conducted their studies.

sample.value: The sample size will be determined by the power required to make claims about performance differences. We will collect data until our results no longer change with the introduction of additional observations.

analyses.value:
We will examine the proportions of individuals in the Treatment condition who pursue each of the following strategies: 1) exploiting their knowledge of the second-best combination in the two periods of the task; 2) exploiting their knowledge of the second-best combination in the first period of the task and exploring a new combination in the second period of the task; 3) exploring a new combination in the first period of the task and exploiting this new knowledge in the second period of the task, in case it yields a higher payoff than the second-best combination or, alternatively, exploiting their knowledge of the second-best combination in the second period of the task, in case the combination used in the first period of the task yields a lower payoff; 4) exploring new combinations in the two periods of the task; 5) exploiting an inferior combination in the second period of the task.

We will further examine the proportions of individuals in the Control condition who pursue each of the following strategies: 1) Exploring a new combination in the second period if the combination found in the first period is below-average; Exploring a new combination in the second period if the combination found in the first period is above-average; 3) Exploiting the same combination in the second period if the combination found in the first period is below-average; 4) Exploiting the same combination in the second period if the combination found in the first period is above-average.

We will use z-tests to compare the proportion of optimal vs dominated strategies in both conditions. 

We will also examine the overall performance of the two conditions. Given that we are interested in the performance of only two groups, we will use t-tests for this comparison.

outliers.value: We do not plan on excluding any outliers, but to consider instead the full spectrum of responses.

dependent.value:
Dependent Variable 1: The main dependent variable of interest in our study is the search behavior of our participants. Given the nature of our task, we code the search behavior of our participants in terms of the two-period exploration-exploitation strategy that they pursue. There are only a small number of potential combinations between exploration and exploitation that participants can use to approach the task. 

Dependent Variable 2: We are also interested in the overall performance of the two conditions. While different strategies have different expected values (that cannot be calculated by our participants) some strategies perform better in a performance environment in which C is high (i.e., 50). By summing the payoffs obtained by participants in the two periods of the task, we are able to determine how different knowledge endowments (or lack thereof) affect performance.

conditions.value:
Participants are randomly assigned to one of two conditions (Control vs Treatment, between-subjects design) adapted from Ederer and Manso (2013).

Participants assigned to the Control condition are informed about the average profit that they can expect to obtain from running a lemonade stand for 100 periods, using different combinations of price, lemon and sugar content, color, and location of the lemonade stand. 

Participants in the Treatment condition receive the same information as participants in the Control condition. In addition, they are also informed of a combination of price (i.e., $8.2), lemon content (i.e., 7%), sugar content (i.e., 3%), color (i.e., Geen), and location (i.e., Business District) that represents the second-best combination, yielding a profit of $85.

Participants in both conditions may use this information to run their own lemonade stand for two periods.

hypothesis.value:
Research Question: How does knowledge about second-best solutions affect search and, consequently, performance?

Hypothesis 1A: Knowledge about second-best solutions reduces search.

Hypothesis 1B: Knowledge about second-best solutions has a negative impact on performance when C (i.e., the ratio between the payoff of the first- and the second-best solution) is high.
